European Defence and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of Europe's intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political entity whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever – one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated – is an illusion.
It is as if one part of a room could be heated while the other part remained cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event echoes across Europe.
When Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to incorporate the new post-communist democracies – which is in the interest of Europe –, a series of essential tasks must be tackled, both within the new democracies and within the European as well as the Atlantic community.
First, Europe must promote community in post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
A living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must thus help its new democracies to become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepening and strengthening civil society.
The more diverse and interconnected European civil society structures become, the better equipped the new democracies will be for membership in the EU, and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and non-profit or public service organisations.
The deeper the level of redistribution is, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that central authorities cannot identify.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely linked to people or their associations.
Authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its renunciation of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation of Munich.
This experience is still a powerful call to vigilance.
The evil must be confronted as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if only governments act.
Government policy arises from the sentiments of civil society, from the people.
Concern about security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept of its security policy.
It should distinguish itself through the ability to make rapid decisions and quickly implement collective decisions - reforms that have been proven necessary by the recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of pan-European security require interventions beyond EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where a UN mandate is not forthcoming, even though intervention is in the interest of many people, all of Europe, indeed even human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
However, there is no preceding English translation available for the given German source sentence.
Tens of thousands of lives and enormous amounts of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the outset of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was taken only timidly.
These shortcomings were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would still be watching the horrors in Kosovo unfold.
Europe cannot forever rely on the United States, especially not with regards to European issues.
It must be capable of finding its own solutions.
It is unimaginable that the EU can maintain its status as a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of finding means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its own territory but also in regions that may one day join it.
Such an EU expansion is only conceivable if it proceeds hand in hand with a bold reform of the EU institutions.
I am confident that the government conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals to advance the union.
But I consider this as the beginning of a process that will perhaps take decades and should be guided by a lasting commitment to accelerate and make the EU's decision-making process more transparent.
A related point to institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be outvoted by the larger ones, while still properly taking into account the size of individual states.
One possible solution is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament, whose members are not directly elected, but chosen by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU - i.e., the current parliament - would thus reflect the size of individual member states, while the second chamber would, with an equal number of representatives for each state, increase equality.
Earlier or later, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution - a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution would require two parts.
Part one would establish the rights and obligations of both European citizens and states, as well as the underlying values, and the significance and objectives of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their principal powers, and their relationships with one another.
Such a fundamental law would not imply an automatic transformation of the current union into the federal superstate feared by euroskeptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, understand it better, see the importance of the EU for their lives, and thereby identify with it.
